# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: affix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:affix/affix] In linguistics, an **affix** is a morpheme that is attached to a word stem to form a new word or word form.
[src:affix/affix] The two main categories are derivational and inflectional affixes.
[src:affix/affix] Derivational affixes, such as *un-*, *-ation*, *anti-*, and *pre-*, introduce a semantic change to the word they are attached to.
[src:affix/affix] Inflectional affixes introduce a syntactic change, such as singular into plural (e.g.
[src:affix/affix] *-(e)s*), or present simple tense into present continuous or past tense by adding *-ing* or *-ed* to an English word.
[src:affix/affix] All of them are bound morphemes by definition; prefixes and suffixes may be separable affixes.
[src:affix/affix] Adding a morpheme at the beginning of a word is called *prefixation*, in the middle *infixation*, and at the end *suffixation*.
[src:affix/affix] When marking text for interlinear glossing, as shown in the third column in the chart above, simple affixes such as prefixes and suffixes are separated from the stem with hyphens.
[src:affix/affix] Affixes that disrupt the stem, or that are themselves discontinuous, are often marked off with angle brackets.
[src:affix/affix] Reduplication is often shown with a tilde.
[src:affix/affix] Affixes which cannot be segmented are marked with a back slash.
[src:affix/affix] Semantically, lexical or semantic affixes often convey more general or abstract meanings than their corresponding free nouns.
[src:affix/affix] Lexical affixes are relatively rare and are used in Wakashan, Salishan, and Chimakuan languages — the presence of these is an areal feature of the Pacific Northwest of North America - where they show little to no resemblance to free nouns with similar meanings.
[src:affix/affix] Some linguists have claimed that these lexical suffixes provide only adverbial or adjectival notions to verbs.
[src:affix/affix] Other linguists disagree, arguing that they may additionally be syntactic arguments just as free nouns are and, thus, equating lexical suffixes with incorporated nouns.
[src:affix/affix] In sentence (1), the verb "wash" is **šak’ʷətəs** where **šak’ʷ-** is the root and **-ət** and **-əs** are inflectional suffixes.
[src:affix/affix] The subject "the woman" is **łə słeniʔ** and the object "the baby" is **łə qeq**.
[src:affix/affix] In this sentence, "the baby" is a free noun.
[src:affix/affix] In sentence (2), "baby" does not appear as a free noun.
[src:affix/affix] Instead it appears as the lexical suffix **-əyəł** which is affixed to the verb root **šk’ʷ-** (which has changed slightly in pronunciation, but this can also be ignored here).
[src:affix/affix] The lexical suffix is neither "the baby" (definite) nor "a baby" (indefinite); such referential changes are routine with incorporated nouns.
[src:affix/affix] In orthography, the terms for affixes may be used for the smaller elements of conjunct characters.
[src:affix/affix] For example, Maya glyphs are generally compounds of a *main sign* and smaller *affixes* joined at its margins.
[src:affix/affix] These are called *prefixes, superfixes, postfixes,* and *subfixes* according to their position to the left, on top, to the right, or at the bottom of the main glyph.
[src:affix/affix] A small glyph placed inside another is called an *infix.* Similar terminology is found with the conjunct consonants of the Indic alphabets.
[src:affix/affix] For example, the Tibetan alphabet utilizes prefix, suffix, superfix, and subfix consonant letters.
[src:affix/agglutination] In linguistics, **agglutination** is a morphological process in which words are formed by stringing together morphemes (word parts), each of which corresponds to a single syntactic feature.
[src:affix/agglutination] Languages that use agglutination widely are called agglutinative languages.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, in the agglutinative Turkish, the word *evlerinizden* ("from your houses") consists of the morphemes *ev-ler-i-n-iz-den*.
[src:affix/agglutination] Agglutinative languages are often contrasted with isolating languages, in which words are monomorphemic, and fusional languages, in which words can be complex, but morphemes may correspond to multiple features.
[src:affix/agglutination] Although agglutination is characteristic of certain language families, this does not mean that when several languages in a certain geographic area are all agglutinative they are necessarily related phylogenetically.
[src:affix/agglutination] In the past, this assumption led linguists to propose the so-called Ural–Altaic language family, which included the Uralic and Turkic languages, as well as Mongolian, Korean, and Japanese.
[src:affix/agglutination] Contemporary linguistics views this proposal as controversial, and some refer to this as a language convergence instead.
[src:affix/agglutination] Another consideration when evaluating the above proposal is that some languages that developed from agglutinative proto-languages lost their agglutinative features.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, contemporary Estonian has shifted towards the fusional type.
[src:affix/agglutination] Examples of agglutinative languages include the Uralic languages, such as Finnish, Estonian, and Hungarian.
[src:affix/agglutination] These have highly agglutinated expressions in daily usage, and most words are bisyllabic or longer.
[src:affix/agglutination] Grammatical information expressed by adpositions in Western Indo-European languages is typically found in suffixes.
[src:affix/agglutination] Hungarian uses extensive agglutination in almost every part of it.
[src:affix/agglutination] The suffixes follow each other in special order based on the role of the suffix, and many can be heaped, one upon the other, resulting in words conveying complex meanings in compacted forms.
[src:affix/agglutination] An example is *fiaiéi*, where the root "fi(ú)-" means "son", the subsequent four vowels are all separate suffixes, and the whole word means "[plural properties] belong to his/her sons".
[src:affix/agglutination] The nested possessive structure and expression of plurals are quite remarkable (note that Hungarian uses no genders).
[src:affix/agglutination] Though Indo-European languages are generally non-agglutinating, there are exceptions.
[src:affix/agglutination] Persian has some features of agglutination, making use of prefixes and suffixes attached to the stems of verbs and nouns.
[src:affix/agglutination] Persian is an SOV language, thus having a head-final phrase structure.
[src:affix/agglutination] Persian utilizes a noun root + plural suffix + case suffix + postposition suffix syntax similar to Turkish.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, the phrase "*Mashinhayeshan-ra negah mikardam*/ماشین‌های‌شان را نگاه می‌کردم" meaning 'I was looking at their cars' lit.
[src:affix/agglutination] Breaking down the first word: ماشین(car)+(ها(ی(plural suffix)+شان(possessive suffix)+را(post-positional suffix) We can see its agglutinative nature and the fact that Persian is able to affix a given number of dependent morphemes to a root morpheme (in this example, car).
[src:affix/agglutination] Almost all Austronesian languages, such as Malay, and most Philippine languages, also belong to this category, thus enabling them to form new words from simple base forms.
[src:affix/agglutination] The Indonesian and Malay word *mempertanggungjawabkan* is formed by adding active-voice, causative and benefactive affixes to the compound verb *tanggung jawab*, which means "to account for".
[src:affix/agglutination] In Tagalog (and its standardised register, Filipino), *nakakapágpabagabag* ("that which is upsetting/disturbing") is formed from the root *bagabag* ("upsetting" or "disquieting").
[src:affix/agglutination] In East Asia, Korean is an agglutinating language.
[src:affix/agglutination] Its uses of '조사', '접사', and '어미' makes Korean agglutinate.
[src:affix/agglutination] They represent tense, time, number, causality, and honorific forms.
[src:affix/agglutination] Japanese is also an agglutinating language, like Korean, adding information such as negation, passive voice, past tense, honorific degree and causality in the verb form.
[src:affix/agglutination] The "-siniz" refers to plural form of you with "-sin" being the singular form, the same way "-im" being "I" ("-im" means "my" not "I".
[src:affix/agglutination] The original editor must have mistaken it for "-yim".
[src:affix/agglutination] This second suffix is used as such "Oraya gideyim" meaning "May I go there" or "When I get there") and "-imiz" making it become "we".
[src:affix/agglutination] Similarly, this suffix means "our" and not "we".
[src:affix/agglutination] In all Dravidian languages, verbal markers are used to convey tense and mood, and usually person (though Malayalam is an exception to the latter).
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, in Tamil, "சாப்பிடுகிறேன்" (*cāppiṭukiṟēṉ*, "I eat") is formed from the verb root சாப்பிடு- (*cāppiṭu-*, "to eat") + the present tense marker -கிற்- (*-kiṟ-*) + the first-person singular suffix -ஏன் (*-ēṉ*).
[src:affix/agglutination] Agglutination is also a notable feature of Basque.
[src:affix/agglutination] Another example would be the declension: *Etxean* = "In the house" where *etxe* = house.
[src:affix/agglutination] Agglutination is used very heavily in most Native American languages, such as the Inuit languages, Nahuatl, Mapudungun, Quechua, Tz'utujil, Kaqchikel, Cha'palaachi and Kʼicheʼ, where one word can contain enough morphemes to convey the meaning of what would be a complex sentence in other languages.
[src:affix/agglutination] Conversely, Navajo contains affixes for some uses, but overlays them in such unpredictable and inseparable ways that it is often referred to as a fusional language.
[src:affix/agglutination] As noted above, it is a typical feature of agglutinative languages that there is a one-to-one correspondence between suffixes and syntactic categories.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, a noun may have separate markers for number, case, possessive or conjunctive usage etc.
[src:affix/agglutination] The order of these affixes is fixed, so we may view any given noun or verb as a stem followed by several inflectional and derivational "slots", i.e. positions in which particular suffixes may occur, and/or preceded by several "slots" for prefixes.
[src:affix/agglutination] It is often the case that the most common instance of a given grammatical category is unmarked, i.e. the corresponding affix is empty.
[src:affix/agglutination] The number of slots for a given part of speech can be surprisingly high.
[src:affix/agglutination] 2. tense: *-(e)ss* (었) for completed (past) action or state; when this slot is empty, the tense is interpreted as present (The 'ss' is pronounced as 't' if it is placed behind a consonant.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, -었어(ess-e) is pronounced as (esse), but -었다(ess-ta) is pronounced as (etta).
[src:affix/agglutination] Moreover, passive and causative verbal forms can be derived by adding suffixes to the base, which could be seen as the null-th slot.
[src:affix/agglutination] Even though some combinations of suffixes are not possible (e.g. only one of the aspect slots may be filled with a non-empty suffix), over 400 verb forms may be formed from a single base.
[src:affix/agglutination] Although most agglutinative languages in Europe and Asia are predominantly suffixing, the Bantu languages of eastern and southern Africa are known for a highly complex mixture of prefixes, suffixes and reduplication.
[src:affix/agglutination] A typical feature of this language family is that nouns fall into noun classes.
[src:affix/agglutination] For each noun class, there are specific singular and plural prefixes, which also serve as markers of agreement between the subject and the verb.
[src:affix/agglutination] Moreover, the noun determines prefixes of all words that modify it and subject determines prefixes of other elements in the same verb phrase.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, the Swahili nouns *-toto* ("child") and *-tu* ("person") fall into class 1, with singular prefix *m-* and plural prefix *wa-*.
[src:affix/agglutination] The noun *-tabu* ("book") falls into class 7, with singular prefix *ki-* and plural prefix *vi-*.
[src:affix/agglutination] The American linguist Joseph Harold Greenberg in his 1960 paper proposed to use the so-called *agglutinative index* to calculate a numerical value that would allow a researcher to compare the "degree of agglutitativeness" of various languages.
[src:affix/agglutination] For Greenberg, *agglutination* means that the morphs are joined only with slight or no modification.
[src:affix/agglutination] A morpheme is said to be automatic if it either takes a single surface form (morph), or if its surface form is determined by phonological rules that hold in all similar instances in that language.
[src:affix/agglutination] A morph juncture—a position in a word where two morphs meet—is considered agglutinative when both morphemes included are automatic.
[src:affix/agglutination] The index of agglutination is equal to the average ratio of the number of agglutinative junctures to the number of morph junctures.
[src:affix/agglutination] Languages with high values of the agglutinative index are agglutinative and with low values of the agglutinative index are fusional.
[src:affix/agglutination] In the same paper, Greenberg proposed several other indices, many of which turn out to be relevant to the study of agglutination.
[src:affix/agglutination] The *synthetic index* is the average number of morphemes per word, with the lowest conceivable value equal to 1 for isolating (analytic) languages and real-life values rarely exceeding 3.
[src:affix/agglutination] The compounding index is equal to the average number of root morphemes per word (as opposed to derivational and inflectional morphemes).
[src:affix/agglutination] The derivational, inflectional, prefixial and suffixial indices correspond respectively to the average number of derivational and inflectional morphemes, prefixes and suffixes.
[src:affix/agglutination] The one-to-one relationship between an affix and its grammatical function may be somewhat complicated by the phonological processes active in the given language.
[src:affix/agglutination] Several examples from Finnish will illustrate how these two rules and other phonological processes lead to diversions from the basic one-to-one relationship between morphs and their syntactic and semantic function.
[src:affix/agglutination] No phonological rule is applied in the declension of *talo* 'house'.
[src:affix/agglutination] However, the second example illustrates several kinds of phonological phenomena.
[src:affix/agglutination] It is possible to construct artificially extreme examples of agglutination, which have no real use, but illustrate the theoretical capability of the grammar to agglutinate.
[src:affix/agglutination] This is not a question of "long words", because some languages permit limitless combinations with compound words, negative clitics or such, which can be (and are) expressed with an analytic structure in actual usage.
[src:affix/agglutination] English is capable of agglutinating morphemes of solely native (Germanic) origin, as *un-whole-some-ness*, but generally speaking the longest words are assembled from forms of Latin or Ancient Greek origin.
[src:affix/agglutination] The classic example is *antidisestablishmentarianism*.
[src:affix/agglutination] Agglutinative languages often have more complex derivational agglutination than isolating languages, so they can do the same to a much larger extent.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, in Hungarian, a word such as *elnemzetietleníthetetlenségnek*, which means "for [the purposes of] undenationalizationability" can find actual use.
[src:affix/agglutination] In the same way, there are the words that have meaning, but probably are never used such as *legeslegmegszentségteleníttethetetlenebbjeitekként*, which means "like the most of most undesecratable ones of you", but is hard to decipher even for native speakers.
[src:affix/agglutination] Using inflectional agglutination, these can be extended.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, the official Guinness world record is Finnish *epäjärjestelmällistyttämättömyydellänsäkäänköhän* "I wonder if – even with his/her quality of not having been made unsystematized".
[src:affix/agglutination] It has the derived word *epäjärjestelmällistyttämättömyys* as the root and is lengthened with the inflectional endings ‑*llänsäkäänköhän*.
[src:affix/agglutination] However, this word is grammatically unusual, because *-kään* "also" is used only in negative clauses, but *-kö* (question) only in question clauses.
[src:affix/agglutination] A very popular Turkish agglutination is *Çekoslovakyalılaştıramadıklarımızdanmışsınız*, meaning "(Apparently / I've heard that) You are one of those that we were not able to convert into Czechoslovaks".
[src:affix/agglutination] This historical reference is used as a joke for the individuals who are hard to change or those who stick out in a group.
[src:affix/agglutination] On the other hand, *Afyonkarahisarlılaştırabildiklerimizdenmişsinizcesine* is a longer word that does not surprise people and means "As if you were one of those we were able to make resemble people from Afyonkarahisar".
[src:affix/agglutination] Georgian is also a highly agglutinative language.
[src:affix/agglutination] For example, the word *gadmosakontrrevolucieleblebisnairebisatvisaco* (გადმოსაკონტრრევოლუციელებლებისნაირებისათვისაცო) would mean "(someone not specified) said that it is also for those who are like the ones who need to be to again/back counter-revolutionized".
[src:affix/agglutination] It was created to ridicule a trend for long compounds in Attic Greek at the time.
[src:affix/agglutination] Slavic languages are not considered agglutinative but fusional.
[src:affix/agglutination] However, extreme derivations similar to ones found in typical agglutinative languages do exist.
[src:affix/agglutination] A famous example is the Bulgarian word *непротивоконституциослователствувайте*, meaning *don't speak against the constitution* and secondarily *don't act against the constitution*.
[src:affix/agglutination] It is composed of just three roots: против *against*, конституция *constitution*, a loan word and therefore devoid of its internal composition and слово *word*.
[src:affix/agglutination] The remaining are bound morphemes for negation (*не*, a proclitic, otherwise written separately in verbs), noun intensifier (*-ателств*), noun-to-verb conversion (*-ува*), imperative mood second person plural ending (*-йте*).
[src:affix/agglutination] It is rather unusual, but finds some usage, e.g. newspaper headlines on 13 July 1991, the day after the current Bulgarian constitution was adopted with much controversy and debate, and even scandals.
[src:affix/agglutination] The words *agglutination* and *agglutinative* come from the Latin word *agglutinare*, 'to glue together'.
[src:affix/agglutination] In linguistics, these words have been in use since 1836, when Wilhelm von Humboldt's posthumously published work *Über die Verschiedenheit des menschlichen Sprachbaues und ihren Einfluß auf die geistige Entwicklung des Menschengeschlechts* lit.
[src:affix/agglutination] 'On the differences of human language construction and its influence on the mental development of mankind' introduced the division of languages into *isolating*, *inflectional*, *agglutinative* and *incorporating*.
[src:affix/agglutination] Especially in some older literature, *agglutinative* is sometimes used as a synonym for *synthetic*.
[src:affix/agglutination] In that case, it embraces what we call agglutinative and inflectional languages, and it is an antonym of *analytic* or *isolating*.
[src:affix/agglutination] Besides the clear etymological motivation (after all, inflectional endings are also "glued" to the stems), this more general usage is justified by the fact that the distinction between agglutinative and inflectional languages is not a sharp one, as we have already seen.
[src:affix/agglutination] The following passage from Lord (1960) demonstrates well the whole range of meanings that the word *agglutination* may have.
[src:affix/agglutination] In natural language processing, languages with rich morphology pose problems of quite a different kind than isolating languages.
[src:affix/agglutination] In the case of agglutinative languages, the main obstacle lies in the large number of word forms that can be obtained from a single root.
[src:affix/agglutination] As we have already seen, the generation of these word forms is somewhat complicated by the phonological processes of the particular language.
[src:affix/agglutination] Although the basic one-to-one relationship between form and syntactic function is not broken in Finnish, the authoritative institution Institute for the Languages of Finland (*Kotus*) lists 51 declension types for Finnish nouns, adjectives, pronouns, and numerals.
[src:affix/agglutination] Even more problems occur with the recognition of word forms.
[src:affix/agglutination] Modern linguistic methods are largely based on the exploitation of corpora; however, when the number of possible word forms is large, any corpus will necessarily contain only a small fraction of them.
[src:affix/agglutination] Hajič (2010) claims that computer space and power are so cheap nowadays that all possible word forms may be generated beforehand and stored in a form of a lexicon listing all possible interpretations of any given word form.
[src:affix/agglutination] (The data structure of the lexicon has to be optimized so that the search is quick and efficient.) According to Hajič, it is the disambiguation of these word forms which is difficult (more so for inflective languages where the ambiguity is high than for agglutinative languages).
[src:affix/agglutination] Other authors do not share Hajič's view that space is no issue and instead of listing all possible word forms in a lexicon, word form analysis is implemented by modules which try to break up the surface form into a sequence of morphemes occurring in an order permissible by the language.
[src:affix/agglutination] The problem of such an analysis is the large number of morpheme boundaries typical for agglutinative languages.
[src:affix/agglutination] A word of an inflectional language has only one ending and therefore the number of possible divisions of a word into the base and the ending is only linear with the length of the word.
[src:affix/agglutination] In an agglutinative language, where several suffixes are concatenated at the end of the word, the number of different divisions which have to be checked for consistency is large.
[src:affix/agglutination] This approach was used for example in the development of a system for Arabic, where agglutination occurs when articles, prepositions and conjunctions are joined with the following word and pronouns are joined with the preceding word.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The Alabama first encountered Europeans when Hernando de Soto arrived in 1540.
[src:affix/alabama-language] (See here for other de Soto contactees) In the 18th century, the French arrived on the Gulf Coast and built a fort at what became Mobile, Alabama.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The *Alibamu* and *Koasati* tribes were part of the Creek Confederacy.
[src:affix/alabama-language] They had less contact with British settlers than other Creek tribes did.
[src:affix/alabama-language] They were the first to leave when British settlers swarmed into the area by the middle of the 18th century, after the land was ceded by the French following the British victory in the French and Indian War.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Under pressure as well by Native American enemies, the Alabama and Coushatta tribes wanted to avoid the powerful Choctaw in present-day Mississippi.
[src:affix/alabama-language] They moved into territories of future states, first into Louisiana and then into Texas.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In 1795, the Coushatta arrived in the Big Thicket area of East Texas.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In 1805, nearly 1,000 Alabama came to Tyler County's Peach Tree Village in East Texas.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The two tribes developed a strong friendship as they roamed and hunted their new land together.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In the early 19th century, the Texas Congress granted each tribe two strips of land along the Trinity River.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Their land was soon taken over by European-American settlers, leaving them homeless.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Sam Houston, the governor of Texas, recommended that the state purchase 1,280 acres (5.2 km2) for the Alabamas.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Although money was appropriated to buy 640 acres (2.6 km2) for the Coushatta, the land was never bought.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Either through marriage or special permission, many Coushatta went to live on the land given to the Alabama.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Other Coushatta had stayed in an area in southern Louisiana near the Red River.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Many of their descendants are enrolled members of the federally recognized Coushatta Tribe of Louisiana.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Alabama and Coushatta towns were divided into "red" and "white" towns.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The "white" towns were responsible for keeping the peace and for providing refuge, while the "red" towns were responsible for conducting military campaigns.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Though they had "red" and "white" towns, the Alabama–Coushatta thought of themselves as a peace-loving people.
[src:affix/alabama-language] By 1820, there were three main Alabama towns and three large Coushatta towns in east Texas, in the region known as the Big Thicket.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In 1854, the Alabama were given 1,280 acres (5.2 km2) in Polk County.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The following year, 640 acres (2.6 km2), also in Polk County, were given to the Coushattas.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The Coushatta claim was disputed by white settlers in 1859.
[src:affix/alabama-language] When the Coushatta lost the land claim, the Alabama invited them to live on their land claim.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The federal government approved a large grant in 1928 to purchase additional land near the reservation; it was granted to the "Alabama and Coushatta tribes." Since that time, the reservation has officially been known as *Alabama–Coushatta*.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Origin narratives focus on the interconnectedness of the tribes.
[src:affix/alabama-language] One narrative states that the two tribes sprouted from either side of a cypress tree.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Another legend was recorded in 1857 from *Se-ko-pe-chi*, one of the oldest Creeks in Indian Territory.
[src:affix/alabama-language] He said that the tribes "sprang out of the ground between the Cohawba and Alabama Rivers." The symbol of the Alabama–Coushatta tribe comes from pre-contact Mississippian culture: two intertwined woodpeckers, now symbolic of the connection between the two tribes.
[src:affix/alabama-language] There are fourteen consonant phonemes in Alabama.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The voiceless stops /p t k/ are typically fortis and unlike in many other Southeastern languages they are not voiced between vowels.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The post-alveolar affricate /tʃ/ is realized as [s] when it occurs as the first member of a consonant cluster and the geminate is realized as [ttʃ].
[src:affix/alabama-language] The only voiced obstruent in Alabama is /b/, which is realized as [m] when it occurs in coda (syllable final) position.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The two nasal phonemes become velar [ŋ] before the velar stop /k/.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In syllable-final position, /h/ is often realized as lengthening of the preceding vowel.
[src:affix/alabama-language] There are three vowel qualities, /i o a/.
[src:affix/alabama-language] Vowels can be nasalized in certain morphological contexts.
[src:affix/alabama-language] In Alabama, the final syllable generally carries the primary stress, except in the case of certain grammatical operations which move the stress.
[src:affix/alabama-language] There is also a pitch accent system with two contrastive tones: high-level and high-falling.
[src:affix/alabama-language] The two phonemic tones have several different allophonic realizations depending on vowel length and neighboring consonants.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Despite its name, NAPA has always been widely used outside the Americas.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] For example, a version of it is the standard for the transcription of Arabic in articles published in the *Zeitschrift der Deutschen Morgenländischen Gesellschaft*, the journal of the German Oriental Society.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Diacritics are more widely used in Americanist notation than in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA), which seeks to use as few diacritics as possible for phonemic distinctions, retaining them only for the dental–alveolar distinction.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Americanist notation relies on diacritics to distinguish many other distinctions that are phonemic in the languages it transcribes.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] On the other hand, Americanist notation uses single letters for most coronal affricates, whereas the IPA requires digraphs.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Otherwise Americanist notation has grown increasingly similar to IPA, and has abandoned many of the more obscure letters it once employed.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Certain symbols in NAPA were once identical to those of the International Phonetic Alphabet, but have become obsolete in the latter, such as ⟨ι⟩.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Over the years, NAPA has drawn closer to the IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] This can be seen, for example, in a comparison of Edward Sapir's earlier and later works.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] However, there remain significant differences.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The influential anthropologist Franz Boas used a somewhat different set of symbols (Boas 1911).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] In 1916, a publication by the American Anthropological Society greatly expanded upon Boas's alphabet.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] This same alphabet was discussed and modified in articles by Bloomfield & Bolling (1927) and Herzog *et al.* (1934).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The Americanist notation may be seen in the journals *American Anthropologist*, *International Journal of American Linguistics*, and *Language*.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Useful sources explaining the symbols – some with comparisons of the alphabets used at different times – are Campbell (1997:xii-xiii), Goddard (1996:10–16), Langacker (1972:xiii-vi), Mithun (1999:xiii-xv), and Odden (2005).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] It is often useful to compare the Americanist tradition with another widespread tradition, the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Americanist phonetic notation does not require a strict harmony among character styles: letters from the Greek and Latin alphabets are used side-by-side.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Another contrasting feature is that, to represent some of the same sounds, the Americanist tradition relies heavily on letters modified with diacritics; whereas the IPA, which reserves diacritics for other specific uses, gave Greek and Latin letters new shapes.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] These differing approaches reflect the traditions' differing philosophies.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The Americanist linguists were interested in a phonetic notation that could be easily created from typefaces of existing orthographies.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] This was seen as more practical and more cost-efficient, as many of the characters chosen already existed in Greek and East European orthographies.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The Western Institute for Endangered Language Documentation (WIELD) has recommended the following conventions since 2016; Note however that WIELD is designed specifically for Native American languages, whereas NAPA, despite its name, is widely used elsewhere, e.g. in Africa.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Glottalization, including ejectives, uses a combining diacritic, e.g. ⟨č̓⟩ or ⟨m̓⟩.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Labialization, velarization, aspiration, voicelessness and prenasalization are as in the IPA, as are pharyngeals, epiglottals, glottals, implosives and clicks.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] About 90% of languages have only one rhotic consonant.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] As a result, rhotic consonants are generally transcribed with the ⟨r⟩ character.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] This usage is common practice in Americanist and also other notational traditions (such as the IPA).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] This lack of detail, although economical and phonologically sound, requires a more careful reading of a given language's phonological description to determine the precise phonetics.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] There are many alternate symbols seen in Americanist transcription.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Below are some equivalent symbols matched with the symbols shown in the consonant chart above.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] According to Pullum & Ladusaw (1996), typical Americanist usage at the time was more-or-less as follows.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] There was, however, little standardization of rhotics, and ⟨ṛ⟩ may be either retroflex or uvular, though as noted above ⟨ṛ⟩ or ⟨ṛ̌⟩ may be a retroflex flap vs ⟨ṛ̃⟩ as a uvular trill.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Apart from the ambiguity of the rhotics below, and minor graphic variants (ȼ g γ for c ɡ ɣ and the placement of the diacritic in g̑ γ̑), this is compatible with the WIELD recommendations.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Only precomposed affricates are shown below; others may be indicated by digraphs (e.g. ⟨dz⟩).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Ejectives and implosives follow the same conventions as in the IPA, apart from the ejective apostrophe being placed above the base letter.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Voiceless, voiced and syllabic consonants may also be C̥, C̬ and C̩, as in IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Aspirated consonants are Cʻ or C̥ʰ / C̬ʱ.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Non-audible release is indicated with superscripting, Vꟲ.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Labialization is C̮ or Cʷ; palatalization is Ꞔ, C⁽ⁱ⁾ or Cʸ; velarization is C⁽ᵘ⁾, and pharyngealization is C̴.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Other airstream mechanisms are pulmonic ingressive C←, ejective Cˀ, implosive Cˁ, click C˂, and lingual ejective (spurt) C˃.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] WIELD recommends the following conventions.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] No distinction is made between front and central for the lowest unrounded vowels.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Diphthongs are e.g. ⟨ai⟩ or ⟨ay⟩, depending on phonological analysis.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] A three-way length distinction may be ⟨a a꞉ a꞉꞉⟩ or ⟨a a· a꞉⟩.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Primary and secondary stress are e.g. ⟨á⟩ and ⟨à⟩.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Voicelessness is e.g. ⟨ḁ⟩, as in the IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Creak, murmur, rhoticity et al. are as in the IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] A long vowel is V꞉ or V·; half-long is V· (raised dot).
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Positional variants are fronted V˂, backed V˃, raised V˄ and lowered V˅.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Bloch & Trager (1942) proposed the following schema, which was never used.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] They use a single dot for central vowels and a dieresis to reverse backness.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The only central vowels with their own letters are ⟨ɨ⟩, which already has a dot, and ⟨ᵻ⟩, which would not be distinct if formed with a dot.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Enclosed in parentheses are rounded vowels.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Apart from ⟨ʚ, ꭤ⟩ and some differences in alignment, it is essentially the IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Chomsky & Halle (1968) proposed the following schema, which was hardly ever used.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] In addition to the table, there was ⟨ə⟩ for an unstressed reduced vowel.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Stress is primary ˈCV or ⟨V́⟩ and secondary ˌCV or ⟨V̀⟩.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Short or intermediate and long or final 'pauses' are ⟨|⟩, ⟨||⟩, as in IPA.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Syllable division is CV.CV, as in IPA, and morpheme boundaries are CV-CV.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The following charts were agreed by committee of the American Anthropological Association in 1916.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The vowel chart is based on the classification of H.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The high central vowels are differentiated by moving the centralizing dot to the left rather than with a cross stroke.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] IPA equivalents are given in a few cases that may not be clear.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The journal *Anthropos* published the alphabet to be used in their articles in 1907.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] It is the same basic system that Sapir and Boas introduced to the United States.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Transcription is italic, without other delimiters.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] Following are symbols that differ among well-known Americanist sources.
[src:affix/americanist-phonetic-notation] The IETF language tags register `fonnapa` as a subtag for text in this notation.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West was born in Dunfermline, Scotland to naval officer Dennis West and Shelagh Gardiner.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] He had two older siblings and one younger.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West attended Bishop Vesey's Grammar School in Sutton Coldfield, England.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] He began his studies at the University of Leicester but withdrew after the first year.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] He later graduated with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) in Far East studies from SOAS University of London in 1988, a Master of Arts (MA) and PhD from Princeton University, and a Master of Science (MSc) in Software Engineering from the University of Westminster.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West's first works concerned Chinese novels of the Ming and Qing dynasties.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] His study of *Romance of the Three Kingdoms* used a new approach to analyse the relationship among the various versions, extrapolating the original text of that novel.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West compiled a catalogue for the Chinese-language library of the English missionary Robert Morrison containing 893 books representing in total some 10,000 string-bound fascicules.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] His subsequent work was in the minority languages of China, especially Khitan, Manchu, and Mongolian.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] He proposed an encoding scheme for the 'Phags-pa script, which was subsequently included in Unicode version 5.0.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West also worked to encode gaming symbols and phonetic characters to the UCS, and worked on encodings for Tangut and Jurchen.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West was the developer of a number of software products and fonts for Microsoft Windows, including BabelPad and BabelMap.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] BabelPad is a Unicode text editor with various tools for entering characters and performing text conversions such as normalization and Unicode casing.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] BabelPad also supports a wide range of encodings, and has input methods for entering Chinese, Mongolian, Manchu, Tibetan, Uyghur and Yi text, as well as for entering individual Unicode characters by their hexadecimal code point value.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] BabelMap is a Unicode character map application that supports all Unicode blocks and characters, and includes various utilities such as pinyin and radical lookup tools for entering Chinese characters.
[src:affix/andrew-west-linguist] West died from a heart attack on 10 July 2025, aged 65.
[src:affix/areal-feature] In geolinguistics, **areal features** are elements shared by languages or dialects in a geographic area, particularly when such features are not descended from a common ancestor or proto-language.
[src:affix/areal-feature] An areal feature is contrasted with genetic relationship determined similarity within the same language family.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Features may diffuse from one dominant language to neighbouring languages (see "sprachbund").
[src:affix/areal-feature] Genetic relationships are represented in the family tree model of language change, and areal relationships are represented in the wave model.
[src:affix/areal-feature] When little or no direct documentation of ancestor languages is available, determining whether the similarity is genetic or merely areal can be difficult.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Edward Sapir notably used evidence of contact and diffusion as a negative tool for genetic reconstruction, treating it as a subject in its own right only at the end of his career (e.g., for the influence of Tibetan on Tocharian).
[src:affix/areal-feature] William Labov in 2007 reconciled the tree and wave models in a general framework based on differences between children and adults in their language learning ability.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Adults do not preserve structural features with sufficient regularity to establish a norm in their community, but children do.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Linguistic features are diffused across an area by contacts among adults.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Languages branch into dialects and thence into related languages through small changes in the course of children's learning processes which accumulate over generations, and when speech communities do not communicate (frequently) with each other, these cumulative changes diverge.
[src:affix/areal-feature] Diffusion of areal features for the most part hinges on low-level phonetic shifts, whereas tree-model transmission includes in addition structural factors such as "grammatical conditioning, word boundaries, and the systemic relations that drive chain shifting".
[src:affix/areal-feature] In some areas with high linguistic diversity, a number of areal features have spread across a set of languages to form a sprachbund (also known as a linguistic area, convergence area or diffusion area).
[src:affix/areal-feature] Some examples are the Balkan sprachbund, Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area, and the languages of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:affix/augmentative] An **augmentative** (abbreviated **aug**) is a morphological form of a word which expresses greater intensity, often in size but also in other attributes.
[src:affix/augmentative] Overaugmenting something often makes it grotesque and so in some languages, augmentatives are used primarily for comical effect or as pejoratives.
[src:affix/augmentative] Many languages have augmentatives for nouns, and some have augmentatives for verbs.
[src:affix/augmentative] Since the early 1990s, the prefix "über-" or "uber-" has also frequently been used as a borrowing from German.
[src:affix/augmentative] The suffix -zilla (from *Godzilla*), expressing a monstrous quality, can also be considered an augmentative form.
[src:affix/augmentative] In some parts of the United Kingdom and the Republic of Ireland, the prefix "old" is used as an augmentative, and a pejorative in some cases.
[src:affix/augmentative] An example of this is using "old’un" or "old one" to describe one's parents/grandparents.
[src:affix/augmentative] In German, there are different ways to build augmentatives.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Swedish, the way to build an augmentative is to add one of many prefixes before the main word, typically a noun, adjective or adverb.
[src:affix/augmentative] Some common prefixes are: *jätte*-, *super*-, *bauta*-, and *mega*-.
[src:affix/augmentative] There are many synonyms to the augmentative *jätte*-.
[src:affix/augmentative] These do not refer to size, only intensity, e.g.
[src:affix/augmentative] *gul* "yellow" to *jättegul* or *skitgul* "very yellow".
[src:affix/augmentative] Like many other augmentative prefixes, *jätte*- is also a noun that can be part of a compound word, e.g.
[src:affix/augmentative] *jättelik* "enormous" (literally "giantlike"), as opposed to *jättelik* "very similar".
[src:affix/augmentative] The use of prefixes to build augmentatives in Swedish is colloquial and is seldom used in formal text and speech, where adjectives and adverbs are used instead.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Modern Greek the usage of augmentative is very common in everyday speech but not quite as common as diminutive forms.
[src:affix/augmentative] The usage of augmentative is considered colloquial and it is not present at all in formal speech.
[src:affix/augmentative] Most nouns in their augmentative form are feminine.
[src:affix/augmentative] This means neuter and masculine nouns become feminine and then an augmentative suffix is added.
[src:affix/augmentative] Suffixes *-accio*, *-accia*, and *-astro*, *-astra*, also exist, but they are used to form pejorative words, with no properly augmentative meaning: *coltellaccio* (< *coltello* 'knife'; gives English *cutlass*); the family name *Carpaccio*.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Portuguese, the most common augmentatives are the masculine *-ão* (sometimes also *-zão* or *-zarrão*) and the feminine *-ona* (or *-zona*), although there are others, less frequently used.
[src:affix/augmentative] *carro* "car", *carrão* "big car"; *homem* "man", *homenzarrão* "big man"; *mulher* "woman", *mulherona* "big woman".
[src:affix/augmentative] Sometimes, especially in Brazilian Portuguese, the masculine augmentative can be applied to a feminine noun, which then becomes grammatically masculine, but with a feminine meaning (e.g.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Romanian there are several augmentative suffixes: *-oi/-oaie*, *-an/-ană* etc.
[src:affix/augmentative] They originate from Latin *-ō* (acc. sg.
[src:affix/augmentative] *-ōnem*), the origin of the other Romance augmentative suffixes.
[src:affix/augmentative] The archaic form has survived unchanged in Banat (and in Aromanian) as *-on'*, *-oan'e*.
[src:affix/augmentative] As in other Romance languages, a feminine base word may have masculine or feminine forms in the augmentative.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Spanish, -o becomes -ón and -a becomes -ona most frequently, but -ote/-ota and -azo/-aza (also meaning *-blow*) are also commonly seen.
[src:affix/augmentative] Others include -udo/-uda, -aco/-aca, -acho/-acha, -uco/-uca, -ucho/-ucha, -astro/-astra and -ejo/-eja.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Bulgarian, as in Russian, mainly with *-ище*.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Polish there is a variety of augmentatives formed with suffixes, for example: żaba (a frog) → żabucha / żabsko / żabisko / żabula; or kamień (a stone) → kamulec / kamior / etc.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Russian there is a variety of augmentatives formed with prefixes (including loans from Latin) and suffixes, including -ище and -ина for example: дом ('house') дом**ище** ('great house') дом**ина** ('huge house').
[src:affix/augmentative] To provide an impression of excessive qualities the suffix -га can be used for example: ветер ('wind'), ветрю**га** ('strong wind').
[src:affix/augmentative] Augmentative nouns are either pejoratives, although distinct pejorative suffixes also exist.
[src:affix/augmentative] All augmentative nouns have female grammatical gender.
[src:affix/augmentative] Some nouns can have their augmentatives formed with different suffixes, for example, see 'kuća' above.
[src:affix/augmentative] In *Hrvatska gramatika*, Barić et al. do not classify adjectives formed with suffixes which intensify an action or property as augmentatives.
[src:affix/augmentative] The augmentative prefixes for adjectives listed in *Hrvatska gramatika* are pre- ("excessively"; or excess of a favorable property), hiper- ("hyper-"), super- and ultra-.
[src:affix/augmentative] According to *Hrvatska enciklopedija*, augmentative verbs surpass their base verb with their intensity.
[src:affix/augmentative] However, by defining augmentative verbs as an action done excessively, *Hrvatska gramatika* only lists pre- ("over-") as an augmentative verb.
[src:affix/augmentative] Form II of the Arabic verb often has an augmentative sense, which may indicate intensity (intensive) or repetition (frequentative).
[src:affix/augmentative] Bantu languages' noun class markers often double as augmentative and diminutive markers, and some have separate classes that are used only as an augmentative or a diminutive.
[src:affix/augmentative] Chichewa noun class 7 prefix *chi-* doubles up as augmentative marker.
[src:affix/augmentative] For example, ***chi**ndege* which is a huge plane as opposed to *ndege* which is just a regular plane.
[src:affix/augmentative] In Esperanto, the *-eg-* infix is included before the final part-of-speech vowel.
[src:affix/augmentative] For example, *domo* (house) becomes *domego* (mansion).
[src:affix/augmentative] Interlingua does not have an augmentative suffix, but international prefixes such as *super-*, *hyper-*, *mega-* can be used as augmentatives.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The **Austronesian languages** (/ˌɔːstrəˈniːʒən/ *AW-strə-NEE-zhən*) are a language family widely spoken throughout Maritime Southeast Asia, parts of Mainland Southeast Asia, Madagascar, the islands of the Pacific Ocean and Taiwan (by Taiwanese indigenous peoples).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] They are spoken by about 386 million people (4.4% of the world population).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This makes it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (one variant standardized as Indonesian), Javanese, Sundanese, Tagalog (standardized as Filipino), Malagasy and Cebuano.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] According to some estimates, the family contains 1,257 languages, which is the second most of any language family.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] In 1706, the Dutch scholar Adriaan Reland first observed similarities between the languages spoken in the South East Asia Archipelago and by peoples on islands in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Wilhelm von Humboldt, Herman van der Tuuk) started to apply the comparative method to the Austronesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The first extensive study on the history of the phonology was made by the German linguist Otto Dempwolff.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] It included a reconstruction of the Proto-Austronesian lexicon.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The term *Austronesian* was coined (as German **austronesisch**) by Wilhelm Schmidt, deriving it from Latin **auster** "south" and Ancient Greek *νῆσος* (*nêsos* "island"), meaning the "Southern Island languages".
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Most Austronesian languages are spoken by the people of Insular Southeast Asia and Oceania.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Only a few languages, such as Peninsular Malay varieties, Jakun, Temuan, Urak Lawoiʼ and the Chamic languages (except Acehnese), are indigenous to mainland Asia, or Malagasy which is the only Austronesian language indigenous to Insular East Africa.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] There are few Austronesian languages which have populations exceeding a few thousand, but a handful have speaking populations in the millions; Indonesian, the most widely spoken, has around 252 million speakers, making it the tenth most-spoken language in the world.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Approximately twenty Austronesian languages are official in their respective countries.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] By the number of languages they include, Austronesian and Niger–Congo are the two largest language families in the world.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] They each contain roughly one-fifth of the world's languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The geographical span of Austronesian was the largest of any language family in the first half of the second millennium CE, before the spread of Indo-European languages in the colonial period.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] It ranges from Madagascar to Easter Island in the eastern Pacific.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] According to Robert Blust (1999), Austronesian is divided into several primary branches, all but one of which are found exclusively in Taiwan.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Formosan languages of Taiwan are grouped into as many as nine first-order subgroups of Austronesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] All Austronesian languages spoken outside the Taiwan mainland (including its offshore Yami language) belong to the Malayo-Polynesian (sometimes called *Extra-Formosan*) branch.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Most Austronesian languages lack a long history of written attestation.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The oldest inscription in the Cham language, the Đông Yên Châu inscription dated to c.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] 350 AD, is the first attestation of any Austronesian language.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Austronesian languages overall possess phoneme inventories which are smaller than the world average.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Around 90% of the Austronesian languages have inventories of 19–25 sounds (15–20 consonants and 4–5 vowels), thus lying at the lower end of the global typical range of 20–37 sounds.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] However, extreme inventories are also found, such as Nemi (New Caledonia) with 43 consonants.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The canonical root type in Proto-Austronesian is disyllabic with the shape CV(C)CVC (C = consonant; V = vowel), and is still found in many Austronesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] In most languages, consonant clusters are only allowed in medial position, and often, there are restrictions for the first element of the cluster.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] There is a common drift to reduce the number of consonants which can appear in final position, e.g.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Buginese, which only allows the two consonants /ŋ/ and /ʔ/ as finals, out of a total number of 18 consonants.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Complete absence of final consonants is observed e.g. in Nias, Malagasy and many Oceanic languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Tonal contrasts are rare in Austronesian languages, although Moken–Moklen and a few languages of the Chamic, South Halmahera–West New Guinea and New Caledonian subgroups do show lexical tone.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Most Austronesian languages are agglutinative languages with a relatively high number of affixes, and clear morpheme boundaries.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Most affixes are prefixes (Malay *ber-jalan* 'walk' < *jalan* 'road'), with a smaller number of suffixes (Tagalog *titis-án* 'ashtray' < *títis* 'ash') and infixes (Roviana *t<in>avete* 'work (noun)' < *tavete* 'work (verb)').
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Reduplication is commonly employed in Austronesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This includes full reduplication (Malay *anak-anak* 'children' < *anak* 'child'; Karo Batak *nipe-nipe* 'caterpillar' < *nipe* 'snake') or partial reduplication (Agta *taktakki* 'legs' < *takki* 'leg', *at-atu* 'puppy' < *atu* 'dog').
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] It is difficult to make generalizations about the languages that make up a family as diverse as Austronesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The word for *eye* in many Austronesian languages is *mata* (from the most northerly Austronesian languages, Formosan languages such as Bunun and Amis all the way south to Māori).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The word for *two* is also stable, in that it appears over the entire range of the Austronesian family, but the forms (e.g.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Bunun *dusa*; Amis *tusa*; Māori *rua*) require some linguistic expertise to recognise.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Austronesian Basic Vocabulary Database gives word lists (coded for cognateness) for approximately 1000 Austronesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The internal structure of the Austronesian languages is complex.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The family consists of many similar and closely related languages with large numbers of dialect continua, making it difficult to recognize boundaries between branches.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The first major step towards high-order subgrouping was Dempwolff's recognition of the Oceanic subgroup (called *Melanesisch* by Dempwolff).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The special position of the languages of Taiwan was first recognized by André-Georges Haudricourt (1965), who divided the Austronesian languages into three subgroups: Northern Austronesian (= Formosan), Eastern Austronesian (= Oceanic), and Western Austronesian (all remaining languages).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] In a study that represents the first lexicostatistical classification of the Austronesian languages, Isidore Dyen (1965) presented a radically different subgrouping scheme.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] He posited 40 first-order subgroups, with the highest degree of diversity found in the area of Melanesia.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Oceanic languages are not recognized, but are distributed over more than 30 of his proposed first-order subgroups.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Dyen's classification was widely criticized and for the most part rejected, but several of his lower-order subgroups are still accepted (e.g. the Cordilleran languages, the Bilic languages or the Murutic languages).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Subsequently, the position of the Formosan languages as the most archaic group of Austronesian languages was recognized by Otto Christian Dahl (1973), followed by proposals from other scholars that the Formosan languages actually make up more than one first-order subgroup of Austronesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Robert Blust (1977) first presented the subgrouping model which is currently accepted by virtually all scholars in the field, with more than one first-order subgroup on Taiwan, and a single first-order branch encompassing all Austronesian languages spoken outside of Taiwan, viz.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The relationships of the Formosan languages to each other and the internal structure of Malayo-Polynesian continue to be debated.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] In addition to Malayo-Polynesian, thirteen Formosan subgroups are broadly accepted.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The seminal article in the classification of Formosan—and, by extension, the top-level structure of Austronesian—is Blust (1999).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Prominent Formosanists (linguists who specialize in Formosan languages) take issue with some of its details, but it remains the point of reference for current linguistic analyses.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Debate centers primarily around the relationships between these families.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Of the classifications presented here, Blust (1999) links two families into a Western Plains group, two more in a Northwestern Formosan group, and three into an Eastern Formosan group, while Li (2008) also links five families into a Northern Formosan group.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Harvey (1982), Chang (2006) and Ross (2012) split Tsouic, and Blust (2013) agrees the group is probably not valid.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Other studies have presented phonological evidence for a reduced Paiwanic family of Paiwanic, Puyuma, Bunun, Amis, and Malayo-Polynesian, but this is not reflected in vocabulary.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Eastern Formosan peoples Basay, Kavalan, and Amis share a homeland motif that has them coming originally from an island called *Sinasay* or *Sanasay*.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Amis, in particular, maintain that they came from the east, and were treated by the Puyuma, amongst whom they settled, as a subservient group.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This classification retains Blust's East Formosan, and unites the other northern languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Li (2008) proposes a Proto-Formosan (F0) ancestor and equates it with Proto-Austronesian (PAN), following the model in Starosta (1995).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Rukai and Tsouic are seen as highly divergent, although the position of Rukai is highly controversial.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Sagart (2021) finds other shared innovations that follow the same pattern.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The fact that the Kradai languages share the numeral system (and other lexical innovations) of pMP suggests that they are a coordinate branch with Malayo-Polynesian, rather than a sister family to Austronesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The Malayo-Polynesian languages are—among other things—characterized by certain sound changes, such as the mergers of Proto-Austronesian (PAN) *t/*C to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian (PMP) *t, and PAN *n/*N to PMP *n, and the shift of PAN *S to PMP *h.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] There appear to have been two great migrations of Austronesian languages that quickly covered large areas, resulting in multiple local groups with little large-scale structure.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The first was Malayo-Polynesian, distributed across the Malay archipelago and Melanesia.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The second migration was that of the Oceanic languages into Polynesia and Micronesia.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] According to Robert Blust, the Formosan languages form nine of the ten primary branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] At least since Sapir (1968), writing in 1949, linguists have generally accepted that the chronology of the dispersal of languages within a given language family can be traced from the area of greatest linguistic variety to that of the least.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] For example, English in North America has large numbers of speakers, but relatively low dialectal diversity, while English in Great Britain has much higher diversity; such low linguistic variety by Sapir's thesis suggests a more recent spread of English in North America.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] While some scholars suspect that the number of principal branches among the Formosan languages may be somewhat less than Blust's estimate of nine (e.g.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Li 2006), there is little contention among linguists with this analysis and the resulting view of the origin and direction of the migration.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] For a recent dissenting analysis, see Peiros (2004).
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The protohistory of the Austronesian people can be traced farther back through time.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] To get an idea of the original homeland of the populations ancestral to the Austronesian peoples (as opposed to strictly linguistic arguments), evidence from archaeology and population genetics may be adduced.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Studies from the science of genetics have produced conflicting outcomes.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Some researchers find evidence for a proto-Austronesian homeland on the Asian mainland (e.g., Melton et al.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] 1998), while others mirror the linguistic research, rejecting an East Asian origin in favor of Taiwan (e.g., Trejaut et al.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Archaeological evidence (e.g., Bellwood 1997) is more consistent, suggesting that the ancestors of the Austronesians spread from the South Chinese mainland to Taiwan at some time around 8,000 years ago.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Evidence from historical linguistics suggests that it is from this island that seafaring peoples migrated, perhaps in distinct waves separated by millennia, to the entire region encompassed by the Austronesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] It is believed that this migration began around 6,000 years ago.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] However, evidence from historical linguistics cannot bridge the gap between those two periods.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The view that linguistic evidence connects Austronesian languages to the Sino-Tibetan ones, as proposed for example by Sagart (2002), is a minority one.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Linguistic analysis of the Proto-Austronesian language stops at the western shores of Taiwan; any related mainland language(s) have not survived.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The only exceptions, the Chamic languages, derive from more recent migration to the mainland.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] However, according to Ostapirat's interpretation of the seriously discussed Austro-Tai hypothesis, the Kra–Dai languages (also known as Tai–Kadai) are exactly those related mainland languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Genealogical links have been proposed between Austronesian and various families of East and Southeast Asia.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] An Austro-Tai proposal linking Austronesian and the Kra-Dai languages of the southeastern continental Asian mainland was first proposed by Paul K.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Benedict, and is supported by Weera Ostapirat, Roger Blench, and Laurent Sagart, based on the traditional comparative method.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Ostapirat (2005) proposes a series of regular correspondences linking the two families and assumes a primary split, with Kra-Dai speakers being the people who stayed behind in their Chinese homeland.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Blench (2004) suggests that, if the connection is valid, the relationship is unlikely to be one of two sister families.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Rather, he suggests that proto-Kra-Dai speakers were Austronesians who migrated to Hainan Island and back to the mainland from the northern Philippines, and that their distinctiveness results from radical restructuring following contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] An extended version of Austro-Tai was hypothesized by Benedict who added the Japonic languages to the proposal as well.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] A link with the Austroasiatic languages in an 'Austric' phylum is based mostly on typological evidence.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] However, there is also morphological evidence of a connection between the conservative Nicobarese languages and Austronesian languages of the Philippines.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Robert Blust supports the hypothesis which connects the lower Yangtze neolithic Austro-Tai entity with the rice-cultivating Austro-Asiatic cultures, assuming the center of East Asian rice domestication, and putative Austric homeland, to be located in the Yunnan/Burma border area.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Under that view, there was an east-west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] French linguist and Sinologist Laurent Sagart considers the Austronesian languages to be related to the Sino-Tibetan languages, and also groups the Kra–Dai languages as more closely related to the Malayo-Polynesian languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Sagart argues for a north-south genetic relationship between Chinese and Austronesian, based on sound correspondences in the basic vocabulary and morphological parallels.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Laurent Sagart (2017) concludes that the possession of the two kinds of millets in Taiwanese Austronesian languages (not just Setaria, as previously thought) places the pre-Austronesians in northeastern China, adjacent to the probable Sino-Tibetan homeland.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] (2017) are also in agreement with Sagart's proposal, in which their analyses show that the predominantly Austronesian Y-DNA haplogroup O3a2b*-P164(xM134) belongs to a newly defined haplogroup O3a2b2-N6 being widely distributed along the eastern coastal regions of Asia, from Korea to Vietnam.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Sagart also groups the Austronesian languages in a recursive-like fashion, placing Kra-Dai as a sister branch of Malayo-Polynesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] His methodology has been found to be spurious by his peers.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Several linguists have proposed that Japanese is genetically related to the Austronesian family, cf.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Some other linguists think it is more plausible that Japanese is not genetically related to the Austronesian languages, but instead was influenced by an Austronesian substratum or adstratum.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Those who propose this scenario suggest that the Austronesian family once covered the islands to the north as well as to the south.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Martine Robbeets (2017) claims that Japanese genetically belongs to the "Transeurasian" (= Macro-Altaic) languages, but underwent lexical influence from "para-Austronesian", a presumed sister language of Proto-Austronesian.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The linguist Ann Kumar (2009) proposed that some Austronesians might have migrated to Japan, possibly an elite-group from Java, and created the Japanese-hierarchical society.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] She also identifies 82 possible cognates between Austronesian and Japanese, however her theory remains very controversial.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The linguist Asha Pereltsvaig criticized Kumar's theory on several points.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The archaeological problem with that theory is that, contrary to the claim that there was no rice farming in China and Korea in prehistoric times, excavations have indicated that rice farming has been practiced in this area since at least 5000 BC.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The pre-Yayoi Japanese lineage was not shared with Southeast Asians, but was shared with Northwest Chinese, Tibetans and Central Asians.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Linguistic problems were also pointed out.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Kumar did not claim that Japanese was an Austronesian language derived from proto-Javanese language, but only that it provided a superstratum language for old Japanese, based on 82 plausible Javanese-Japanese cognates, mostly related to rice farming.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] In 2001, Stanley Starosta proposed a new language family named East Asian, that includes all primary language families in the broader East Asia region except Japonic and Koreanic.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This proposed family consists of two branches, Austronesian and Sino-Tibetan-Yangzian, with the Kra-Dai family considered to be a branch of Austronesian, and "Yangzian" to be a new sister branch of Sino-Tibetan consisting of the Austroasiatic and Hmong–Mien languages.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This proposal was further researched by linguists like Michael D.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Larish in 2006, who also included the Japonic and Koreanic languages in the macrofamily.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] The proposal has since been adopted by linguists such as George van Driem, albeit without the inclusion of Japonic and Koreanic.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Blevins (2007) proposed that the Austronesian and the Ongan protolanguage are the descendants of an Austronesian–Ongan protolanguage.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] This view is not supported by mainstream linguists and remains very controversial.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Robert Blust rejects Blevins' proposal as far-fetched and based solely on chance resemblances and methodologically flawed comparisons.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] Most Austronesian languages have Latin-based writing systems today.
[src:affix/austronesian-languages] is used with hundreds and thousands and before qualifiers.
